{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":14039,"record_hash":"sha256:986532e935a724983ca2f55aa98dee4d70c7896c9a856e9b8fe8697176ae5cd7","timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:32:42.773Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/agent-session-capture/future-use-cases.md\n+# Future Use Cases\n+\n+This document records the product direction the first agentlog POC should point\n+toward. These use cases are not implemented by the POC, but they shape the data\n+model.\n+\n+## 1. Session Handoff\n+\n+A developer starts an agent session on one machine and wants to continue it on\n+another machine, possibly with another agent.\n+\n+Examples:\n+\n+- Claude Code starts the planning locally, then OpenClaw continues on a remote\n+  machine where the repository is already available.\n+- OpenClaw starts work on a remote machine, then the user continues locally so\n+  they can run a desktop app or device-specific tests.\n+\n+For this to work later, GitButler needs to capture enough session context into\n+GitMeta, move that metadata through Git transport, and expose it on the other\n+side in a form that another agent can use. The POC does not serialize, push,\n+fetch, or resume a session, but its project-scoped session records should be\n+durable enough to make that possible.\n+\n+## 2. Sharing Session Details\n+\n+A developer uses an agent to produce a change and opens a pull request. Reviewers\n+should eventually be able to open a GitButler web view showing what happened in\n+the agent session:\n+\n+- user prompts\n+- assistant responses\n+- tool calls\n+- planning depth\n+- discussed edge cases\n+- follow-up questions\n+\n+This helps reviewers understand whether the generated work was carefully guided\n+or shallowly prompted. It also creates examples of good prompting patterns for a\n+team. A reviewer may later ask a follow-up question against that session context,\n+for example whether a payments edge case was considered.\n+\n+The POC only captures redacted session records. It does not create web links,\n+publish metadata, or attach sessions to pull requests.\n+\n+## Many-to-Many Relationships\n+\n+Sessions and code review objects are not one-to-one.\n+\n+One branch or pull request may involve multiple sessions:\n+\n+```text\n+PR A\n+  -> session 1\n+  -> session 2\n+```\n+\n+One session may also contribute to multiple branches or pull requests, especially\n+in GitButler where a worktree can contain several active branches and a user may\n+commit different hunks to different destinations:\n+\n+```text\n+session 1\n+  -> feature branch\n+  -> bugfix branch\n+```\n+\n+The durable object should therefore be the project-scoped GitButler agent\n+session. Branches, commits, changes, and pull requests should later reference\n+session keys rather than own the transcript data directly.\n+\n+Future relationship keys can look like this:\n+\n+```text\n+<branch/change/commit target>\n+  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n+```\n+\n+That shape supports:\n+\n+- sessions that exist before code is written\n+- one session associated with many branch or review objects\n+- many sessions associated with one branch or review object\n+- branch or commit associations being added after capture\n+\n+## POC Direction\n+\n+The first POC should:\n+\n+- write redacted, shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` keys\n+- keep session data on the `project` target by default\n+- use a durable session key independent of branches and commits\n+- keep source metadata separate from per-record transcript envelopes\n+- avoid storing local-only paths, cwd values, branches, or raw provider session\n+  ids\n+- avoid serialization, push, fetch, sync, branch inference, and PR association\n+\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:32:42.773Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}